initial_story: in recent years, classical convolutional neural networks (cnns) have beenapplied for image recognition successfully. quantum convolutional neuralnetworks (qcnns) are proposed as a novel generalization to cnns by usingquantum mechanisms. the quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient trainingprocess in qcnns by reducing the size of input from $n$ to $log_2n$. this paperimplements and compares both cnns and qcnns by testing losses and predictionaccuracy on three commonly used datasets. the datasets include the mnisthand-written digits, fashion mnist and cat/dog face images. additionally, dataaugmentation (da), a technique commonly used in cnns to improve the performanceof classification by generating similar images based on original inputs, isalso implemented in qcnns. surprisingly, the results showed that dataaugmentation didn't improve qcnns performance. the reasons and logic behindthis result are discussed, hoping to expand our understanding of quantummachine learning theory.
stories: Classical convolutional neural networks (CNNS) have achieved significant success in image recognition in recent years. A novel innovation, quantum convolutional neural networks (QCNNS), generalizes CNNS by harnessing quantum mechanisms. These quantum techniques drastically streamline the training process, reducing input size from n to log2n. This study compared both CNNS and QCNNS via experimentation with three standard datasets, including MNIST hand-written digits, fashion MNIST, and cat/dog images. Data augmentation (DA), often utilized in CNNS to enhance classification, was also incorporated into QCNNS. Unexpectedly, data augmentation exhibited no performance boost in QCNNS. The reasoning behind this outcome is analyzed, aiming to broaden our comprehension of quantum machine learning principles.

Classical convolutional neural networks (CNNS) have seen remarkable achievements in recent years, with a notable outcome in image recognition. A pioneering advancement, quantum convolutional neural networks (QCNNS), has elevated CNNS by harnessing quantum technologies. These quantum approaches noticeably accelerate the training process, shrinking input size from n to log2n. This research compared CNNS and QCNNS through experimentation on three benchmark datasets, including MNIST hand-written digits, fashion MNIST, and cat/dog images. Data augmentation, commonly used in CNNS to strengthen classification, was also employed in QCNNS. Surprisingly, data augmentation did not boost QCNNS performance, and the rationale behind this finding is explored to shed light on quantum machine learning principles.

Renewed efforts in convolutional neural networks (CNNS) have yielded impressive results in image recognition, with quantum convolutional neural networks (QCNNS) now pushing the boundaries further by integrating quantum technologies. QCNNS' application of quantum principles can significantly hasten the training process, reducing input size from n to log2n. Through experiments on three benchmark datasets - including MNIST, fashion MNIST, and cat/dog images - the study juxtaposed CNNS and QCNNS performance. Despite the use of data augmentation, a common practice in enhancing classification in CNNS, results showed no gain in QCNNS performance; the underlying reason for this discovery is being examined to better comprehend quantum machine learning concepts.
